<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / BNFL to shed 2,000 Sellafield jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Nuclear Fuels plans to cut a third of its workforce at its
Sellafield reprocessing plant in Cumbria over the next five years in an
effort to cut costs, the company said yesterday. It will also shed 200 jobs
at Chapelcross in Dumfries.
Mr Grahame Smith, director of BNFL's UK group, said the company had to cut
costs by 20 per cent or Pounds 100m a year for the next five years in order
to remain competitive.
He said he was confident of a viable future for BNFL's UK business,
'providing we continue to help our customers to reduce their cost base and
compete with fossil fuels'.
BNFL's customers are the UK nuclear generators for which it reprocesses
spent fuel.
BNFL will reduce the number of jobs at Sellafield by 2,000 over the next
five years, but officials stressed that it plans to make no compulsory
redundancies. The job losses would leave 5,000 full-time employees at
Sellafield and Chapelcross. The job losses will not affect BNFL's
controversial Thorp reprocessing plant which employs 1,500 people, the
company said.
But opponents said the job losses would have an adverse impact on the local
economy similar to what would have been felt if the government had refused
permission for the Thorp plant, for which ministers gave the go-ahead in
February. BNFL had used the impact on the local economy as an argument for
going ahead with Thorp. Cumbria County Council called the job cuts 'a major
blow'. Mr Alan Clark, chairman of the council's economic development
committee, said: 'This is desperately disappointing news.' Sellafield is the
largest employer in the area, where unemployment rates at 9.6 per cent are
high.
The company's announcement comes just a week after the UK government
embarked on an all-embracing review of the nuclear power industry. BNFL said
the timing of its announcement had nothing to do with the review and that,
unlike Nuclear Electric, one of its nuclear generator customers, it had not
been lobbying for privatisation.
'We have to get into a strong business position: that is what is behind the
job losses,' an official said.
The company said the nuclear generators were having to compete in an
increasingly competitive electricity supply sector and the company needed to
cut its costs for the services it provides.
</TEXT>
