<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Landlords criticised on energy efficiency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Owners of accommodation for private rental make the least investment in
energy efficiency, according to a report published today by the Institute
for Fiscal Studies.
Although many of these households will suffer the greatest impact from the
imposition of value added tax on fuel, they are in the worst position to
take steps to cut their bills, it says.
The conclusion highlights one of the weaknesses of the Energy Saving Trust,
whose future was the subject of a tense and prolonged Commons committee
meeting yesterday.
The trust, which is intended to subsidise energy saving measures by
households, plans to direct almost all of its schemes at owner-occupiers.
Some of the poorest households, particularly in urban areas, may not
qualify.
Yesterday, MPs on the Commons environment committee were grilling Ms Clare
Spottiswoode, director-general of Ofgas, the gas regulator, about her
unwillingness to pass on the costs of the trust's schemes to gas customers.
She said she would consider each scheme on its merits in the light of its
cost-effectiveness.
The IFS report says 'there are certain areas in which market failures may
deter households from making rational decisions regarding energy efficiency
investments'.
While tenants in rented housing would benefit from lower fuel bills if the
property were well insulated, responsibility for decisions about the fabric
of the building usually lies with the landlord.
The IFS report calls for improved information for tenants about energy
efficiency. 'Only if tenants are willing to pay higher rents for more energy
efficient properties will landlords face an incentive to make energy
efficiency investments,' it argues.
Household Energy Efficiency in the UK. May issue of Fiscal Studies. IFS, 7
Ridgmount St, London WC1E 7AE. Pounds 8.
</TEXT>
