<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / UDM joins Edwards bidding consortium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Union of Democratic Mineworkers yesterday formed a powerful bidding
partnership with the former commercial director of British Coal as it
emerged that each of the country's mining regions is likely to attract at
least three tenders.
The UDM consortium with Mr Malcolm Edwards and Coal Investments, the quoted
company he heads, is to consider bidding for the three English regions in
the forthcoming privatisation. Coal Investments is thought to be bidding for
the south Wales region - but without the UDM.
If the consortium decides to proceed it is likely to face competition from
bidders including RJB Mining, Ryan Group and at least two management buy-out
teams.
By yesterday, the final day to register an interest, each of the regions for
sale had attracted at least four potential bidders. However, some companies
 -such as RTZ, the world's biggest mining company - are thought unlikely to
make a bid after studying what is on offer.
The UDM decided to link with Coal Investments after its original partner,
Jim Walter Resources, withdrew due to problems in the US. Mr Edwards said
workers would be offered shares in the group.
The following lists some of the parties thought to have registered to
'pre-qualify' to bid. Scotland: Mining (Scotland); Ryan and Miller joint
venture; Caledonian Mining; RJB Mining; RTZ.
North-east: Ryan/Alcan joint venture; UDM/Coal Investments; management
buy-out team led by Mr Bob Siddall, British Coal opencast director;
Caledonian; RJB; RTZ.
Central North: UDM/Coal Investments; management buy-out team led by Mr Alan
Houghton, regional director; management buy-out team led by Mr Siddall; RJB;
RTZ.
Central south: UDM/Coal Investments; management buy-out team led by Mr
Siddall; RJB; RTZ.
South Wales: management buy-out team led by Mr Bryan Riddleston, opencast
director in south Wales; RJB; Coal Investments; Ryan Group; Caledonian.
Companies have paid Pounds 15,000 for each pre-qualification registration
and another Pounds 5,000 in regard to stand-alone mines which British Coal
has closed but is offering for sale. Bidding is expected in September.
</TEXT>
