<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Tory election campaign hit by political truce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The moratorium on campaigning after the death of John Smith, the Labour
leader, appears to have done serious damage to the Conservative campaign for
the European elections in south-west England.
While Liberal Democrat activists campaigned quietly last week in the
south-west, where they have their highest hopes of winning seats, the
Conservatives restricted themselves to 'housekeeping chores' such as
labelling election addresses.
The Liberal Democrats avoided high-profile 'media events' or canvassing in
strongly Labour areas, but several MPs visited the region.
One Conservative official said the campaign 'hiatus' had been difficult to
maintain: 'I don't think that people appreciate the extraordinary difficulty
in the shutting of a campaign machine. Once it's stopped, it's very
difficult to start up.'
The Conservatives have not achieved the display of posters they had hoped
for, and will mount only two or three more visits to the region by cabinet
ministers before the final week of the campaign.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, visited Cornwall on Monday, while the
chancellor, Mr Kenneth Clarke, was in Dorset yesterday, in trips designed to
boost local activists' morale and demonstrate that the party is vigorously
contesting the region.
The campaign is complicated by the south-west's large areas and sparse
population covered in each constituency.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party's leader, will visit each south-west
constituency at least four times duringthe campaign, while there will be a
visit from at least one of the party's MPs each day.
</TEXT>
