<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Poll leaders face up to pitfalls: Labour's popularity has a
downside
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is the election Labour cannot lose, but may not win. Even Conservative
strategists admit privately that Labour will add to the 45 seats it holds in
the outgoing European parliament. But the party's campaign managers are
painfully aware of the dangers in being so far ahead.
Before the formal opening of the campaign on Monday, Labour's senior
officials spent much time trying to douse expectations that the party would
win at least 60 of the 84 seats in mainland Britain.
It was all to no avail. An opinion poll by ICM in the Daily Express
newspaper predicts that Labour will win 61 seats; Mr David Butler, the
Oxford University psephologist, forecasts a haul of between 52 and 66.
Against this background, a result that gave Labour fewer than 60 seats would
look disappointing, while a haul of fewer than 50 would cast doubts on the
party's ability to translate its opinion-poll lead into support in the
voting booths.
Labour's strategy is to maximise support by fighting a twin-track campaign
focusing on the government's domestic record and its difficulties over
Britain's place in Europe.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the acting party leader, signalled the shape of the
campaign at the party's first election press conference when she spent as
much time on domestic issues such as tax, crime and health as she did on
Europe.
When Labour does talk about European issues, it is largely in terms of the
government's record: the embarrassing about-turn by Mr John Major, the prime
minister, on qualified majority voting in the Council of Ministers; the
government's failure to take up European Union funds to combat fraud; the
cost of reforms to the Common Agricultural Policy.
The party has blunted Conservative attacks on its own commitment to Europe
by insisting on the retention of the British veto in important areas, and by
proposing radical reforms of the CAP - the EU's most expensive programme.
But it is less keen to discuss its own approach to thorny issues such as the
scope of reforms to EU institutions at the 1996 inter-governmental
conference and the possibility of a referendum on the next steps to economic
and monetary union.
Labour's hope is that its robust defence of the British national interest in
Europe will make it easier for disgruntled Conservatives to register a
protest vote against the government.
The big danger, especially in the south of England, is that maverick Tories
will switch to the Liberal Democrats. To combat that possibility, Labour has
resurrected the 'wasted vote' argument that has served it well in successive
general elections.
Tactical voting worked largely in favour of the Liberal Democrats in the May
local elections. But if its strategy succeeds, Labour could win Conservative
seats - including London north-west and south-east, Lincolnshire and South
Humberside, Norfolk, and Bedfordshire and Milton Keynes.
It has hopes, too, in a batch of southern and Midlands Tory seats which
could go to any of the three main parties. These include Hertfordshire, Kent
East, Hampshire North and Oxford, Sussex South, the Cotswolds and Hereford
and Shropshire. In Hertfordshire, the Liberal Democrats are mounting a
strong challenge on the back of a good performance in the local elections.
Labour activists in the constituencies are less circumspect about the
party's chances than the cautious officials in London. For example, the
Conservatives have held Bedfordshire and Milton Keynes for 15 years. Yet
local Labour campaigners believe the party may win as much as 41.3 per cent
of the vote in the constituency, with the Tories on 33 per cent.
Labour is also benefiting from the emergence of anti-Europe candidates, such
as the 24 standing for the UK Independence party. Such candidates will
almost certainly cream off some votes which would otherwise have gone to the
Conservatives.
Local activists say another factor is emerging - a surge of sympathy for the
party after the death of John Smith, which has galvanised local supporters
into canvassing for Labour. More important, it may help ensure that a high
proportion of Labour supporters turn out on polling day. That could be the
key to victory. But it is a factor Labour would rather have done without.
</TEXT>
