<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Lib Dems pledge retention of 'effective veto'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats yesterday sought to gloss over the party's disarray
over Britain's ability to block decisions in Brussels as Mr Charles Kennedy
said it backed the retention of an 'effective national veto'. The Liberal
Democrat president said the party's suggestion for a 'double majority'
system for taking important decisions in the European Union's Council of
Ministers amounted to such a veto.
His remarks came less than 24 hours after Sir David Steel, the party's
foreign affairs spokesman, said in Cornwall that the EU would be
'stultified' if it did not abandon the national veto in favour of qualified
majority voting.
The Tories last night seized on the apparent discrepancy, calling on Mr
Paddy Ashdown to explain his party's position.
Sir Norman Fowler, the Tory chairman, used an open letter to the Liberal
Democrat leader to highlight Sir David's comments. He said the veto was 'the
most crucial constitutional issue in these elections'.
Earlier Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, acknowledged that in spite
of the Conservatives' decision to make preservation of the veto the
centrepiece of their campaign, the outcome of the June 9 elections would not
affect Britain's ability to block controversial legislation. Mr Hurd
accepted that the Strasbourg assembly had no remit to remove the veto and
that other leading countries in the EU were as committed as Britain to
retaining it.
But any increase in the number of Labour or Liberal Democrat members in the
parliament would over time give support to the case of some smaller EU
members for a move to majority voting on constitutional issues, he said.
In spite of his distaste for his own party's Euro-sceptics, Mr Hurd said the
policies of the main opposition parties would undervalue 'the role of the
nation state' in Europe. He refused to accept statements from Mr Jack
Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, earlier this week that committed
Labour to retaining a veto.
Confusion over the Liberal Democrats' position was triggered on Monday when
Mr Ashdown backed away from abandoning the veto. The party has been anxious
to add a sceptical note to its pro-European stance to win Tory votes in
southern England.
According to Sir Norman's letter, Mr Ashdown said last December that his
party wanted ministers to 'make decisions in public without single national
vetoes'.
The Liberal Democrat manifesto commits the party to working for an extension
of qualified majority voting. But it avoids direct reference to the veto,
suggesting that the system be reformed to require a double majority for
'particularly important issues'.
This double majority would consist of three-quarters of member states and
the votes of states representing three-uarters of the EU's population.
A Guardian/ICM poll suggests today that the Conservatives could be left with
only six seats in the European elections. The figures are: Labour 47 per
cent, Conservatives 26 per cent, Liberal Democrats 23 per cent, SNP 2 per
cent, Greens 1 per cent, Plaid Cymru 1 per cent.
These voting intentions could leave Labour with 65 seats, the Liberal
Democrats with 12 and the Tories six.
</TEXT>
