<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Haiti embargo 'leaky'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MALPASSE, HAITI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US ambassador to Haiti said yesterday that a three-day-old total trade
embargo clamped on the Caribbean nation had been violated repeatedly, Reuter
reports from Malpasse, Haiti.
Ambassador William Swing said at the border with the Dominican Republic that
oil was coming in from Haiti's neighbour and acknowledged the embargo had
been broken several times since it was imposed at midnight on Saturday. He
was referring to reports that boats loaded with fuel entered the southern
Haitian port of Jacmel this week. Mr Swing spent about 15 minutes at the
Malpasse crossing, through which much of the smuggled fuel and other
contraband goods pass. Minutes before he arrived, Haitian entrepeneurs in
rowboats docked on Lake Saumatre's shore with illegally imported fuel.
The UN imposed the embargo on Haiti to try to force intransigent military
leaders to allow democratically elected President Jean-Bertrand Aristide to
return to power. The military toppled Aristide in a bloody coup 32 months
ago.
</TEXT>
