talks on a productivity-linked incentive scheme after they had rejected a 30
per cent wage increase.
The engineers began a go-slow on May 16 to back demands for wage parity with
their higher-paid counterparts in Air India, the country's international air
carrier.
Indian Airlines, in the red since private airlines were allowed to compete
against it three years ago, said earlier it could not afford to pay what
would have amounted to a 90 per cent wage rise. It lost more than Rs100m
(Pounds 2.1m) in revenues during the go-slow.
