<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Inflation warning on UK rates
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UK interest rates will have to be raised by a full percentage point in the
coming months if inflation is to be kept below the government's target of 4
per cent, a leading economic research body warned yesterday.
Raising rates might be politically unwelcome for the government, but the new
climate of openness means that the Bank of England increasingly has the
upper hand in setting inflation policy, the National Institute of Economic
and Social Research says.
'(The government) has allowed a situation to develop in which it is
difficult for the bank's advice on interest rate moves to be rejected,' the
report adds, saying the bank is increasingly inclined to approve increases.
Report, Page 12
