<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Bond and equity prices hit by concern over European rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bond and equity prices across Europe fell heavily yesterday as markets
reached the unwelcome conclusion that a 20-month run of falling interest
rates had come to an end.
Prices fell sharply after the Bundesbank called off a planned auction of
four-year notes because of insufficient demand from bond market traders,
which followed warnings from the bank that further cuts in interest rates
were not planned.
At the same time, apprehension returned that the US Federal Reserve might
continue to tighten credit policy, despite having lifted its key interest
rates only last week.
In the UK, the FT-SE 100 Index plummeted in the afternoon as investors
flinched at the prospect of upward pressure on interest rates. It closed
68.4 points, or 2.21 per cent lower, at a 1994 low of 3,020.7.
The CAC-40 index in Paris fell 48.91, or 2.3 per cent, to 2,084.41, while
Frankfurt continued to pay for the recent relative strength of the market.
The Dax index fell 39.95, or 1.8 per cent, to 2,158.77.
Wall Street ignored the unsettled mood in Europe. The Dow Jones Industrial
Average, which tracked US bond prices throughout the session finished up
10.13 at 3,755.3 after a Treasury auction of new five-year notes was
completed successfully.
The downturn in Europe was touched off by Mr Hans Tietmeyer, president of
the Bundesbank, who had suggested on Monday that German interest rates might
be left unchanged. Market concerns over this statement were exacerbated
yesterday by a relatively small reduction in money rates at the bank's
weekly securities repurchase auction, used to inject short-term liquidity
into money markets.
The mood soured even more when the Bundesbank called off a planned auction
of four-year notes because of insufficient demand from bond market traders,
disappointed by the outcome of the repurchase auction.
'What happened today is an absolute embarrassment for the Bundesbank and it
has behaved in an amateurish way,' said one analyst in Frankfurt. In his
view, there had been enough demand in the market but the Bundesbank was not
willing to raise funds at the current high yields.
Prices for the June contract of the German government bond future on Liffe,
the London futures and options exchange, fell during trading to the year's
low of 93.3 but recovered slightly later to 93.54, down 0.7 of a point on
the day. The policy-making council of the Bundesbank is due to meet today
for its fortnightly discussion of monetary policy but the market does not
expect the central bank to announce a change in official interest rates.
UK government bonds traded near the year's lows, reaching 103 1/2 in late
trading, down  15/16 . Gilts were also depressed by a higher-than-expected
price realised at the Bank of England's auction of the government's first
convertible gilt since 1987.
In London, pressure on equity prices came from the stock index futures
market where the June contract on the FT-SE 100 fell below 3,000 to a hefty
discount against the stock market. A computer-driven sell-off in stock index
futures appeared to originate from a US securities house.
UK market strategists expressed highly bearish views at the close, pointing
out that the equity market chart forecasters see little support for shares
above the Footsie 2,550 level.
There was little response in London to the announcement that US durable
goods orders for April showed a gain of only 0.1 per cent, suggesting less
pressure for another rise in US interest rates. The dollar also came under
pressure yesterday, prompted by the weaker-than-expected durable goods
orders, closing in London at DM1.6447 against the D-Mark, a pfennig down on
the intra-day high of DM1.6545.
Concern over the signs of a change of official stance on German rates
increased after a Bundesbank council member warned of the 'inflation
potential' of the continued growth of German M3 money supply.
Rise in US durable goods orders, Page 5; Too many dollars, Page 25;
Greenspan opposes legislation to control derivatives, Page 26; Lex, Page 26;
International bonds, Page 37; Currencies, Page 39; World stocks, Page 45;
London stocks, Page 48
</TEXT>
