<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAY 94 / Eurotunnel to launch rights issue at big discount today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel is planning to launch its Pounds 850m rights issue this morning
at a price close to the minimum which would allow its vital Pounds 1.6bn
refinancing to take place.
The issue price is expected to be about 260p for each Eurotunnel unit. This
would be 27 per cent below yesterday's 355p closing market price in London,
a significant discount which reflects the uncertainties about the future
revenues of the Channel tunnel operator.
The expected price is only about 10p above the 250p floor that would permit
Eurotunnel to raise sufficient equity finance to cover its pressing
financial requirements. The company has authority to issue only 350m new
shares.
The rights issue will be Eurotunnel's biggest equity fund raising and one of
the biggest cash calls by a UK company.
Investment institutions have been reluctant to underwrite the share offer.
Their concern is that all earnings from the tunnel will be swallowed by
interest payments on about Pounds 8bn of debt until at least 1998 and there
will be no dividend until 2003.
Eurotunnel's financial advisers, SG Warburg and Banque Indosuez, were
yesterday able to begin getting commitments from institutions to underwrite
the shares after the company's 220 banks gave formal approval to their
Pounds 700m portion of the refinancing, more than a week after the deadline.
The banks are providing senior debt, or a loan which ranks ahead of all
existing facilities.
One fund manager said: 'Frankly, we were not keen to take the underwriting.
However, Warburg can be very persuasive.' Brokers said the underwriting
challenge was made more difficult by the sharp fall yesterday in the UK
stock market. However, the price of Eurotunnel units, an unusual security
twinning UK and French shares, fell only 5p to 355p.
A significant role in supporting the share issue was played by Swiss Banking
Corporation, which had agreed to provide primary underwriting for a third of
the whole share offer. It tried yesterday with SG Warburg and Banque
Indosuez to find sub-underwriters to reduce its exposure.
Without the refinancing, Eurotunnel faced a liquidity crisis, only four
years after it last came close to calling in the receivers. By next month,
it will have exhausted all its cash reserves.
The costs of completing the tunnel were well above original forecasts. Its
problems have been compounded by the late start of freight and passenger
services, which means revenues in early years of operation will be lower
than it had hoped.
London stocks, Page 48
</TEXT>
