<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / International Company News: German metals group faces new
risk provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Metallgesellschaft, the German metals, mining and industrial group at the
brink of collapse in January after running up massive losses in oil futures
trading via a New York subsidiary, will have to make further provisions. The
group said last night it would have to cover newly-identified risks in the
US.
It refused to say how big the provisions would be. However, the group made
clear they were needed to cover risks arising in respect of special
contracts between MG Corp, the New York subsidiary which nearly caused
Metallgesellschaft's downfall, and Castle Energy, a small US oil refinery.
Further risks arose because of contracts under which MG Corp agreed to
supply oil and other energy products to industrial customers in the US.
Metallgesellschaft said it would fund the provisions via the sale of its
entire 80 per cent stake in Buderus, an engineering company considered one
of the jewels in the Metallgesellschaft crown. It will also have to dispose
of Lehnkering Montan Transport company and the group's head office site in
the centre of Frankfurt.
Based on the DM1.5bn (Dollars 909m) market value of Buderus, these sales are
likely to raise well in excess of DM1bn. The shares in Buderus will be
placed via a consortium of banks in a way which ensures they are widely
distributed, Metallgesellschaft said.
These revelations, contained in a statement issued after
Metallgesellschaft's supervisory board met yesterday, are likely to shock
investors today. Shares in Germany's 14th largest industrial group have
risen dramatically in recent weeks, reflecting confidence that the worst of
the group's problems have been dealt with by January's DM3.4bn rescue
package.
The disclosure that the 80 per cent stake in Buderus, which has a 25 per
cent market share in the German heating equipment market, will have to go is
likely to prove especially surprising. In February, Mr Kajo Neukirchen,
Metallgesellschaft's chief executive, said there were no plans to sell the
company. Buderus last year made net profits of DM69m and had turnover of
DM2.77bn.
MG Corp's relationship with Castle Energy was characterised by a series of
refining contracts, the most remarkable of which was MG Corp's agreement to
pay Castle a fixed rate of Dollars 5 per barrel above the standard market
price for the benchmark west Texas intermediate crude oil to the year 2000.
</TEXT>
