<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / International Company News: Trelleborg recovers as financial
costs fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Trelleborg, the Swedish mining and metals group, posted a SKr200m (Dollars
26.08m) swing into the black in the first quarter. The turnround came on the
back of lower financial costs and better results from associate companies.
The figures keep it on track for a positive full-year result after two years
of heavy losses.
Group profit after financial items amounted to SKr8m, compared with a
SKr192m loss a year earlier.
The improvement came in spite of a drop in sales, to SKr4.65bn from
SKr5.66bn, and a deterioration in operating profit to SKr67m from SKr170m.
Adjusted for disposals and restructuring, sales were up 2 per cent and
operating income was SKr95m higher than a year ago.
The group benefited from a SKr5.5bn drop in net debt and lower interest
rates, enabling it to cut financial costs by SKr145m to SKr109m.
It also had a SKr50m contribution from associate companies, instead of the
SKr108m loss it suffered in the first quarter of 1993. This reflected a
better performance at Falconbridge, a nickel producer, and a contribution
from Munksjo, a paper and packaging group.
</TEXT>
