Newspapers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Argus Newspapers, the South African press group in which Mr Tony O'Reilly's
Independent Newspapers has bought a controlling shareholding, will today
release a pre-listing statement showing unaudited group turnover of R706.7m
(Dollars 193m) for the year to March and earnings of R29m.
Earnings have been adjusted to take account of discontinued operations, such
as the Sunday Star, and the sale of a majority interest in The Sowetan,
South Africa's biggest selling daily, to a consortium of black investors.
The company is forecasting turnover of R795m and earnings of R32.6m for the
current year. In a calculation based on 45.1m shares in issue, audited pro
forma earnings for the year to March were 64 cents a share. Net asset value
was 384 cents a share.
Argus Holdings and JCI directors will retire from the Argus Newspapers board
prior to the listing and Mr Liam Healy and Mr James Parkinson, managing
director and financial director of Independent, will join the board.
