<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Supermarket price war hits Jeyes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Jeyes Group shares plunged 11 per cent yesterday to 335p as the household
products manufacturer warned shareholders that the supermarket price war in
the UK was taking a toll on first half profits.
The warning comes less than a week household products group Reckitt &amp; Colman
issued its own grim trading statement. It is also Jeyes's second warning in
less than a year, following the gloomy statement in June which wiped 28 per
cent off the group's market value.
Mr Jimmy Moir, chief executive, said the UK business had been particularly
affected by increased demand for generic products and aggressive
discounting. Britain represents some 50 per cent of Jeyes profits.
Margins are estimated to have fallen from between 8 and 10 per cent to about
6 to 8 per cent.
Jeyes's cost-cutting programme has also been more expensive and slower to
implement than had previously been expected, Mr Moir said. The benefits
would not now feed through until the second half. Globol in Germany and the
other international businesses were trading according to expectations, the
group said.
</TEXT>
