<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Orion Publishing plans stock market
flotation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Orion Publishing Group, the general book publisher which in 1992 acquired
George Weidenfeld Holdings, has announced that it is planning a stock market
flotation.
To that end, it has completed a Pounds 4m funding package, led by Baring
Communications Equity, Europe's newest and largest media fund, to reduce its
borrowings and provide working capital. It has also appointed as
non-executive chairman Sir John Cuckney, chairman either previously or
currently of many companies including Westland, 3i, Maxwell Pensioners Trust
and Royal Insurance. Orion was co-founded at the end of 1991 by Mr Peter
Roche, Ms Rosemary Cheetham and Mr Anthony Cheetham, now its chief
executive.
Orion stated that its operating profits more than doubled from Pounds
268,000 to Pounds 583,000 in 1993.
Leading the sales increase were Vikram Seth's A Suitable Boy, Alan Clark's
Diaries, Maeve Binchy's The Copper Beech and Nigel Mansell's Mansell and
Williams.
The paperback division contributed a first-time Pounds 3.7m to the sales
figure; sales in the Orion division grew to Pounds 2.8m (Pounds 1.1m).
</TEXT>
