<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Enlarged Casket rises to Pounds 3.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strong demand from abroad helped Casket, Britain's second-largest bicycle
manufacturer, boost annual pre-tax profits by 27 per cent to Pounds 3.6m.
The company, which claims 25 per cent of the UK market, increased exports by
26 per cent. Profits for the year to end-March were also helped by the
Pounds 1.3m acquisition of a German bicycle company in November, which
contributed Pounds 395,000 at the pre-tax level. Sales were 8 per cent
higher at Pounds 103.8m.
Mr Joe Smith, chief executive, said the underlying bicycle business had
shown like-for-like growth of 18.5 per cent in the year. Demand for Casket's
range of brands had been particularly strong in Germany, France and Ireland,
he said.
The results included the final costs of a long-running legal action over
accounting practices at Kingsley &amp; Forester, a clothing company merged with
Casket in 1988. The group incurred net exceptional costs of Pounds 453,000,
bringing the total costs of the six-year suit to about Pounds 650,000.
The final dividend is increased to 0.7p making a 1.1p (0.8p) total. Earnings
rose by 26 per cent to 3.19p.
</TEXT>
