<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / UK Company News: French buy for Coutts Consulting - Placing
and open offer to fund GBA purchase for up to FFr85.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Coutts Consulting Group, the career consultancy, outplacement and
residential training company, yesterday agreed to acquire GBA Group of
France for a maximum FFr85.9m (Pounds 10.1m).
The proposed acquisition of GBA, one of the leading outplacement and career
counselling groups in France with 130 employees, will consolidate Coutts'
position as Europe's largest outplacement group with 33 offices in six
countries.
Mr Stephen Johnson, chief executive, said the deal would enable the expanded
group to serve its multinational clients across Europe better. He said the
expansion of outplacement operations into continental Europe had been a
vital element in the strategy for developing the group.
Coutts will pay an initial FFr47.2m, including FFr39.7m in cash, with the
balance satisfied through the issue of 971,366 shares to the vendors. Up to
a further Pounds 4.5m will be paid subject to GBA meeting profit targets in
1994 and 1995.
GBA reported pre-tax profits of FFr7.7m for 1993.
The acquisition will be funded in part through a placing and open offer at
85p designed to raise Pounds 6.4m including Pounds 1.1m net of new money.
The shares are being offered on the basis of 8 new shares for every 29
existing shares and 13.137 new shares for every 100 convertible preference
shares.
The 7.56m new shares have been conditionally placed with institutional
shareholders by Collins Stewart, subject to claw-back. Coutts' shares closed
unchanged yesterday at 91p.
Part of the proceeds of the share issue will be used to pay Pounds 730,000
of dividend arrears on convertible preference shares, enabling the group to
resume dividend payments on the ordinary shares at the interim stage later
this year.
The company has undergone a substantial restructuring over the past 30
months, including replacing Mr Barry Topple, its chief executive, and
appointing Sir Kit McMahon, former chairman of Midland Bank, as
non-executive chairman.
Following the acquisition and the completion of the sale of Winkfield Place,
the group's vacant Berkshire property, for Pounds 1.4m due at the end of
May, the enlarged group will have net borrowings of Pounds 4m, equivalent to
gearing of about 50 per cent.
</TEXT>
