<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / US and Japan agree to resume trade talks: Breakthrough has
muted welcome in Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US and Japan yesterday agreed to resume negotiations on a trade
'framework' which Washington expects will produce increased exports in
specific sectors and a reduction of Japan's trade surplus.
Agreement was announced after five days of talks in Washington and a phone
call between President Bill Clinton and prime minister Tsutomu Hata. They
congratulated each other on ending three months of stand-off and vowed to
strengthen the bilateral relationship.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, said sectoral talks would begin
immediately on cars and car parts, insurance and government procurement. He
also hopes to launch discussions 'as soon as possible' in other disputed
areas, such as financial services, glass and intellectual property.
The agreement reflects an improved political climate between the two
countries. It has become apparent that the failure of the February 11 summit
between President Clinton and Japan's then prime minister, Mr Morihiro
Hosokawa, resulted from deep suspicion on both sides. The Japanese thought
the US was pressing them to accept fixed market shares, as it did in the
case of semiconductors; the US thought Tokyo was once again negotiating a
meaningless deal which would not produce results.
It was Mr Hata - then foreign minister - who remarked that the US would not
trust Japan unless it agreed to numerical indicators, while Japan would not
trust the US if it did. Turbulence in the foreign exchange markets and the
prospect that the entire relationship was in trouble forced both sides to
work out their differences.
Their dispute had centred on a US demand for market-opening agreements that
contained 'objective criteria' to measure progress. 'We have confirmed that
we are not seeking numerical targets,' Mr Kantor said.
'Objective criteria will provide the basis for deciding if the agreements
succeed or fail to meet their purpose to achieve concrete results.' Each
group of sector negotiators will work out a set of objective criteria. In
Tokyo, officials were guarded in their view of the breakthrough and stressed
that the agreement was only one step towards resolving a wide array of
issues over which Japan and the US remain at odds.
Mr Koji Kakizawa, foreign minister, said in announcing the latest agreement
that the two sides had agreed not to use numerical targets as 'objective
criteria' for measuring progress in opening Japan's markets. Mr Kakizawa
said, in his view, the US would not impose sanctions based on such criteria.
Japanese business leaders welcomed the breakthrough. Mr Shoichiro Toyoda,
chairman of Toyota Motor and chairman-elect of Keidanren, Japan's Federation
of Economic Organisations, said the resumption of the talks was welcome but
the issue of greater imports of foreign vehicle parts should be decided by
private industry.
US officials have said they would like to reach sectoral agreements in time
for them to be signed at the Group of Seven summit in July. However, Mr
Kantor said the new framework did not contain a timetable for reaching
specific agreements. 'Both countries are committed to moving as quickly as
possible.'
Japanese bank governor sees growth barrier, Page 5
US test for 'dead fish' theory, Page 7
Boost for dollar, Page 35
</TEXT>
