<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Competitiveness - The White Paper: Safety worries over
sell-off are dismissed - Air traffic control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday set the stage for the first full privatisation of a
country's air traffic control system by proposing to sell the Civil Aviation
Authority's National Air Traffic Services (NATS).
After a one-month consultation period with the aviation industry, the
government hopes to have the legislation passed in the next parliamentary
session and to launch the flotation of NATS at the end of next year or early
in 1996.
Mr Christopher Chataway, chairman of the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA),
said the privatisation of NATS would probably be similar to the flotation of
other UK utilities.
Shares in the new company, which would become a privatised contractor to the
CAA, would be offered to the public, aimed at small shareholders as well as
big institutions and corporate investors.
However, a limit is expected to be set on the number of shares that big
groups would be able to buy in the privatised company, Mr Chataway said. The
move would be designed to limit shareholdings by large air traffic control
users such as airlines and airport operators.
The government is also likely to impose a limit on foreign shareholdings.
Both British Airways and British Midland Airways welcomed the government's
proposals, which they said would give the privatised NATS access to capital
markets and greater impetus to improve and modernise the country's air
traffic control infrastructure.
But Sir Michael Bishop, British Midland's chairman, said the government
would have to consider 'very carefully' the impact on airline competition of
allowing airlines to take ownership of NATS. 'We oppose the majority control
of NATS by any airline or group of airlines,' he said.
BAA, the airports operator, said that it would not be interested in taking a
stake in NATS.
Mr Chataway said that splitting the CAA's regulatory activities and its air
traffic control arm would provide greater transparency between regulation
and air traffic control services.
But the main reason for privatisation was to give NATS access to financial
markets so that it could secure its heavy funding needs to modernise and
expand air traffic control services. Investment at NATS is running at Pounds
150m a year compared with only Pounds 20m 10 years ago.
NATS plans to invest around Pounds 650m over the next five years and to
concentrate its operations at two new centres: the en-route centre at
Swanwick, Hampshire, and a Scottish Centre at Prestwick, Ayrshire.
The privatised company would absorb 5,500 of the CAA's current staff of
7,000. NATS' annual turnover is about Pounds 500m, with the bulk of its
income drawn from the provision of en route, approach and airport traffic
control services.
Mr Chataway said the CAA was keen to see the Ministry of Defence continuing
joint operation with NATS. At present there are about 400 MoD staff
integrated in air traffic control operations including some 300 military
controllers. The relationship could continue with a contract between the MoD
and NATS.
Mr Chataway said the CAA was satisfied that privatisation would not
adversely affect the safety of air transport. 'It is difficult to believe
that private is inherently more dangerous than public,' he said, adding that
both BA and BAA had been no less safe since privatisation.
However, ever since privatisation was first mooted, critics have warned of
the potential safety implications of turning over air traffic control to the
private sector. Some air traffic controllers also warned this month that
they would fight 'tooth and nail' against privatisation.
</TEXT>
