<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Competitiveness - The White Paper: Right to advice backed by
extra Pounds 87m over 3 years - Careers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Careers Service will receive an extra Pounds 87m over three years to
provide advice and education in schools, but the government has spelt out in
greater detail than previously what it expects in return.
For the first time it has specified at what ages guidance and advice should
be given independently, with the aim of providing young people with better
signposts at a time when career options are being offered.
Advice will be given at the ages of 13, 15 and at 17 (for those still in
full-time education).
For the first time, young people will have an 'entitlement' to such
guidance, and it details the sort of information that will have to be given
to parents after interviews.
Until recently the service concentrated on advising and placing 16-year-old
school-leavers in jobs, with schools making help available on course
choices. This will now be provided by the Careers Service. The government
last year transferred the duty in England and Wales of providing a careers
service from local education authorities to the employment secretary.
The employment department is inviting bids from local interests, including
education authorities and Training and Enterprise Councils, which manage
government training schemes, to run the service.
Mr Rob Stokes, president of the Institute of Careers Advisers, said he
welcomed the new entitlements. He said surveys had shown a deterioration in
careers guidance and advice. He estimated that if the Careers Service chose
to spend the extra money on advisers, then some 900 more could be recruited.
He said: 'We also welcome the fact that the government wants advice to be
independent at a time when impartial advice is very necessary. It could be
in the financial interests of schools for example, to persuade young people
to stay on at school.'
</TEXT>
