<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Competitiveness - The White Paper: Employers and unions give
welcome to apprentice plan - Training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employers and union leaders welcomed the announcement of the extension of
the 'modern apprenticeship' to students leaving full-time education aged 18
and over.
The initiative, called the 'accelerated modern apprenticeship', builds on
the scheme announced last November.
The original scheme is aimed at 16-year-olds who have left full-time
education and it intends to offer high-quality training to technician and
supervisory levels - areas where the UK has a severe shortage of workers.
The government will provide an additional Pounds 107m for the accelerated
scheme, if industry provides the training places.
The Engineering Training Authority, one of 14 organisations which is
piloting the original scheme, said yesterday: 'This new development is one
we have been calling for. Because there are higher staying-on rates, the
pool of young people we can draw from at 16 is becoming smaller.
In addition, as far as engineering is concerned we welcome people who can
draw upon a sound education up to the age of 18.'
The modern apprenticeship, which is about to be piloted in 14 industrial
sectors, will offer higher-quality training than is generally available to
young people on Youth Training.
The initiative announced yesterday will raise the number of people being
trained to NVQ level 3, the vocational equivalent of two A-levels, from
150,000 to about 200,000.
A number of organisations, including the Confederation of British Industry,
were expecting the government to make a significant announcement on progress
towards introducing training credits, or vouchers, to all people aged 16 to
19. -
Criticisms over the content and structure of new vocational qualifications
will be addressed in a review of all National Vocational Qualifications and
General National Vocational Qualifications, to be completed by April 1996.
</TEXT>
