<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Competitiveness - The White Paper: Clarke curbs Heseltine
ambitions - Political view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine has never been prone to understatement. So his claim
yesterday that he had produced a 'formidable agenda for change and
improvement across the public and private sectors' was unsurprising.
But after five months of work by the cabinet's most senior ministers, the
white paper disclosed a more complex reality. The ministers have analysed
the problems facing the British economy. They have come up with a number of
small but worthwhile initiatives.
But they are still uncertain - and in many cases divided - on the overall
prescription. The finished product bore the marks of a document which had
seen the initial ambitions of Mr Heseltine firmly reined in by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor.
The central political point the government was determined to make was that
it cares about business and it cares about the ability of British companies
to compete in the world.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, thinks his predecessor got it wrong
during the 1980s when initial indifference towards the country's
manufacturing base later turned into malign neglect. He believes the
competitive challenge to Europe from the so-called Asian 'tigers' is still
seriously underestimated. He admires the innovative culture which allows the
US constantly to regenerate its economy.
From that perspective it was essential to present a detailed analysis of the
problems facing industry and an audit of the impact on business of
government policies.
The analysis in the white paper is its strongest point. It is the most
comprehensive study of the performance of British industry and its
relationship with government since 1979. The idea that it is entirely for
the markets to decide what and how much Britain sells abroad has been
quietly buried.
Mr Heseltine and Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, are long-time
political allies. Between them - and with the strong support of the prime
minister - they have added substance to the recognition that high-quality
education and training is critical to the success of British industry.
Among others in the cabinet committee who contributed enthusiastically to
the project were Mr William Waldegrave, science minister, and Mr John
MacGregor, transport secretary.
But the Treasury was less impressed. From the outset it suspected Mr
Heseltine of clinging to the interventionist ambitions he formulated during
the 1980s. Mr Clarke insisted that the white paper could not pre-empt any
decisions in the forthcoming public spending round. He made it clear that he
was not interested in any grandiose industrial strategy.
The Treasury was also hesitant about the whole concept of competitiveness.
It was keen on the document's essentially liberal approach to de-regulation,
privatisation and open markets.
But economic orthodoxy says that, while companies can improve their
competitiveness, nations cannot. The Treasury would have preferred a
'productivity' white paper. The result, ministers acknowledged last night,
was a document which acknowledges that government has a vital role in
underpinning industrial success, but remains unsure of where to draw the
line between support and intervention.
The cabinet committee which produced the white paper will become a permanent
fixture. Mr Major stressed that he was looking to the long term.
Competitiveness is not an issue that will go away. But the government will
have to decide whether it wants a policy for industry or an industrial
policy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
    P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
