<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Council reform threat to landscape
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Reorganisation of local government may jeopardise the effective management
of rights of way and areas of outstanding natural beauty, the Countryside
Commission warned yesterday.
The commission, which advises the government on the English landscape, told
Sir John Banham, chairman of the Local Government Commission, that the move
to unitary authorities could lead to a fragmentation of specialist
countryside teams.
'Where counties are split up, we shall hope to see robust arrangements put
into place for joint work on strategic planning and countryside management,'
the commission said. It has set a target for local authorities to ensure
that all 120,000 miles of public rights of way in England are open and
clearly marked by the year 2000.
