<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Finance companies step up IT spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A majority of financial services companies will increase spending on
information technology this year for the first time since 1989, in spite of
numerous project failures, a survey by the consultancy Price Waterhouse has
found, Alan Cane writes.
The survey of 82 organisations with annual IT budgets ranging from less than
Pounds 5m to more than Pounds 10m found that 57 per cent expected to
increase their rate of IT spending. Last year only 30 per cent predicted a
rise in spending.
The survey also revealed a high rate of project failure, with a quarter of
respondents admitting that most projects had been delivered late or over
budget.
IT project failures have increased as companies have used technologies to
attempt to seize competitive advantage, often without a clear understanding
of what is involved.
Price Waterhouse Financial Services IT Survey, Publications Office,
Southwark Towers, 32 London Bridge Street, London SE1 9SY. Free.
