<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Radio station numbers may surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Radio Authority yesterday offered the possibility of licensing as many
as 150 new commercial radio services in the UK - virtually doubling the
existing number of services.
The new stations, which could go on air from the beginning of 1996, will be
a mixture of large metropolitan stations and more local services.
The authority, the regulatory body for commercial radio, rejected a plea
that the new frequencies between 105MHz and 108MHz should be used to create
a fourth national commercial radio network.
Mr Richard Branson's Virgin Group, which won a national medium-wave
frequency for its 1215 pop station, lobbied heavily for a new national FM
station.
The option chosen will allow up to two new FM services in most large
metropolitan areas and a number of local services.
The authority said yesterday that its chosen option offered the greatest
flexibility and would also accommodate 'a wide variety of types of radio
service, while at the same time broadening choice for the largest number of
listeners'.
Lord Chalfont, chairman of the authority, said the mixture of licences
advertised would depend on demand.
Commercial radio is expanding fast in the UK. Five new regional stations
begin broadcasting on September 1, and applications for four new London
stations close next month.
