<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Ferry group plans two rail bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sea Containers, the container and Hoverspeed ferries group, plans to bid for
two British Rail franchises, but on terms which fall outside the
government's guidelines.
The group would make its offers conditional on obtaining a long lease on the
rail track concerned and on acquiring its own rolling stock. Bids on these
terms would be regarded as 'non-compliant' but would still have to be
considered by Mr Roger Salmon, the rail franchising director.
Normally the government would require train operators to rent track from
Railtrack, the company created to own track and signalling. It also expects
most operators to lease their rolling stock.
Sea Containers is considering bids for BR's Great Western franchise running
from London Paddington and the South West Trains franchise from London
Waterloo.
The franchises would complement Sea Containers' ferry operations between the
mainland and the Isle of Wight.
The franchises, which are expected to attract management buy-out bids, are
in the first round of BR routes to be privatised in 1995.
'We would want to lease our own right of way for 99 years, effectively for
ever, and maintain the track and signalling ourselves,' said Mr James
Sherwood, president of Sea Containers. 'We would also ultimately want to
supply our own rolling stock though we would start by leasing BR stock.'
Mr Sherwood, whose company owns the Orient Express train service, the only
private passenger service to run on BR track, has called for 50-year
franchises, instead of the periods of seven to 15 years suggested by the
government.
He described the Treasury decision to seek a 5.6 per cent return, rising to
8 per cent, on BR's assets as 'absurd'. 'The government should have written
down BR's asset values, to create a company with a sensible capital base.'
The present franchising framework, involving leased rolling stock and rented
track and stations, appeared to have been designed to attract management
buy-out teams. He added: 'The railway network will run down because no one
will be putting any capital in. You can't really control your destiny
because you could lose your franchise at any moment. BR staff will form
groups and take over franchises with Pounds 100 of capital. They will just
be selling their expertise.'
If Sea Containers won a franchise it would seek cost reductions and increase
the marketing of train services. 'We would put on all the usual pressures to
get an efficient transport system,' Mr Sherwood said.
</TEXT>
