<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Deputy IMF head to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The International Monetary Fund yesterday announced that Mr Richard Erb
would be stepping down next week after 10 years as its deputy managing
director.
The number two slot at the Washington-based IMF, which is normally within
the US's gift while the top post is filled by a European, will be taken by
Mr Stanley Fischer, an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and a former chief economist at the World Bank, the IMF's sister
institution.
The IMF is also considering a management restructuring that could give it
three deputy managing directors under Mr Michel Camdessus, the managing
director, in the same way that the World Bank has placed three managing
directors under its president, Mr Lewis Preston.
But officials are still debating how to make clear that Mr Fischer, as the
US appointee, would be the principal deputy, and how to avoid simply adding
an extra layer of bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
