<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / EU auditing 'unintelligible'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Court of Auditors, the European Union's main financial watchdog, suffers
from 'top heavy' senior management and is not professional enough in
fighting fraud in the EU budget, Mr Jo Carey, a former UK Treasury official
and expert on EU finances, said yesterday. In evidence to the House of
Lords' European communities committee, Mr Carey criticised the EU's 'quite
unintelligible' financial controls and said the lack of accountability of
many senior officials encouraged waste. Many experts believe waste totals at
least 5 per cent of EU spending, with much of the fraud due to abuse of farm
subsidies. Mr Carey said the court's efforts to pinpoint fraud ranged from
reports akin to 'slightly haphazard investigative journalism' to documents
which were rigorously argued and 'objective and relevant to policy'.
</TEXT>
