<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Privatisation to devastate jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Privatisation in Europe could cost more than 800,000 jobs by 1999 as
sheltered nationalised industries face tougher competition, a study by six
European economic research institutes warns today. The Ereco network of
research institutes says that more than 120 companies in the European Union
and the European Free Trade Association, employing more than 3.5m people and
with annual sales of Ecu400bn (Pounds 308bn), are candidates for
privatisation. Ereco's forecast suggests more than one in five of the labour
force in these companies will lose their jobs. The job losses would be
concentrated in France, where 290,000 are expected to go, while Italy would
lose 180,000 and Germany 140,000. Many jobs will disappear in
telecommunications, an estimated 268,000, followed by energy (250,000) and
transport (77,000).
The Ereco estimates are based on Britain's experience of privatisation and
subsequent corporate restructuring. UK privatised industries including
British Telecom, British Gas, British Airways, British Steel and the
electricity supply companies shed more than 300,000 jobs in the 1980s. It
predicts that more than 1.1m jobs could be lost if restructuring is
especially severe. But 'perhaps only 500,000 jobs will be shed' if output
growth turns out to be particularly strong in the newly privatised
industries or if governments take action to save jobs.
</TEXT>
