<DATE>940525
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Review promises boost for business: White paper aims to make
Britain more competitive; Pounds 300m extra for training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK government launched its long-awaited white paper on boosting
Britain's competitiveness yesterday with a promise to raise standards of
vocational education and training and provide a better climate in which
business can operate.
The 163-page document, presented with much razzmatazz by Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, contained a multitude of
initiatives and suggestions covering such diverse areas as employment,
management, communications and infrastructure, innovation, export promotion
and proposals to secure more prompt payment of bills for small companies.
But many of the measures in the paper were existing ideas repackaged and
brought together to constitute a strategy. The white paper itself admitted
it was 'in effect a snapshot of work in hand across the government'. Mr John
Major, the prime minister, told a press conference, however, that it was
'rubbish' to suggest there was nothing new in the document. 'There are no
short-term fixes in the white paper but a long-term look at the country's
competitiveness into the next century,' he said. Mr Heseltine said his paper
contained 61 new proposals.
In a rowdy House of Commons, Mr Heseltine said the white paper - 'an agenda
for change and improvement across the public and private sectors' - would
not lead to any overall increase in planned public expenditure. This was in
spite of the government's intention to provide an extra Pounds 300m over the
three financial years to 1997-98 for education and training.
Shortly after Mr Heseltine sat down, Mr David Hunt, the employment
secretary, announced that the government was considering how to put into
effect recommendations from the Health and Safety Commission that would
remove 40 per cent of regulations affecting most businesses 'without
adversely affecting health and safety conditions'.
For his part, Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, announced a
consultation paper on privatising the UK's air traffic control system.
National Air Traffic Services may be floated on the stock exchange, becoming
a private sector contractor to the Civil Aviation Authority.
The white paper was given a scornful reception by Labour. Mr Robin Cook, the
shadow trade secretary, congratulated Mr Heseltine on his 'glitzy'
presentation 'which puts it in the coffee table class of white papers'. But
he said 'the gloss rubs off very easily'.
The white paper, Mr Cook said, was an admission of Britain's competitiveness
problem, adding: 'This is a bankrupt statement from a government on the
verge of liquidation.'
The paper itself said Britain has 'an enormous task' correcting more than
100 years of relative economic decline. It said that improvements in the
1980s meant that the country was 'now back in touch with the leaders, but
there is a lot of ground to make up'.
A cabinet committee, comprising Mr Heseltine and other senior ministers
responsible for the report, will continue to monitor competitiveness and the
effects of the white paper.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, said the committee would 'move on to things
which still need to be done'. He made clear he would be looking at how far
UK companies had achieved the right balance in paying out a greater
proportion of profits in dividends than continental companies. The broad
coverage of the white paper reflects the view of the Department of Trade and
Industry that there is no single cause or no small number of causes for the
UK's competitiveness problems.
In focusing on many facets of the economy, the white paper is intended to
provide ministers with a check list to judge future progress towards making
government policy more friendly to business in an increasingly competitive
world economy.
The check list aspect of the white paper was applauded by Mr Howard Davies,
director-general of the Confederation of British Industry. 'The real value
of the white paper will depend on how it influences government policy in the
future. We shall use the analysis to argue our case for a tax regime which
favours industrial investment, and to press the case for public spending on
training programmes,' he said. The paper was given a generally warm welcome
by industry and commerce. Mr Graham MacKenzie, director-general of the
Engineering Employers' Federation, said it was the nearest to an industrial
strategy that he had seen from this government. 'We are especially pleased
with the education and training measures to strengthen school qualifications
and career guidance,' he said.
To raise educational standards, the government plans to introduce a new
general diploma in England and Wales to provide a 'quality check' that
school pupils have good general certificate of secondary education results,
'more and better' vocational courses for 14- to 16-year-olds and a review of
vocational training standards by the end of 1996. It plans to provide more
help for the transition from school to work and strengthen work-based
training.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, said that 'by 2000 the 16-year-old
school-leaver will be as dead as the dodo'.
Mr Hunt said the Employment Department plans wide-ranging consultations on
the introduction of a voucher system for 16- to 19-year-olds to buy their
own education and training.
The white paper also underlined the government's intention to increase help
for companies, and especially small companies, so that they can improve
their management skills and be given better access to innovation and export
promotion.
In answer to long standing complaints from small companies, the government
will introduce a range of measures to encourage companies to pay bills
promptly. Lord Strathclyde, small companies minister, threatened that the
government would review the case for legislation to improve payment
discipline in two years unless 'significant improvement' has taken place.
Page 10
Clarke curbs Heseltine's ambitions
MPs' proposals rejected
Economy's standing given frank assessment
Page 11
Unique sell-off
Back to the classroom
Page 23
Editorial Comment
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
