<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAY 94 / Morgan Stanley to monitor Dollars 2bn aid for PLO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Palestine Liberation Organisation said yesterday it had chosen Morgan
Stanley Asset Management, fund management arm of the US-based investment
bank, to monitor more than Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.3bn) in international aid
committed to the West Bank and Gaza Strip over the next five years.
The appointment was made to allay international fears about the control and
direction of the funds, particularly that they should not be diverted to
political purposes.
Morgan Stanley has had significant business interests in the Arab Middle
East but has also advised Israel in arranging debt finance for its
US-guaranteed loans programme. The bank's MSAM division has about Dollars
50bn in assets under management.
In a statement from its Tunis headquarters, the PLO said the involvement of
Morgan Stanley would 'help assure contributing nations that the funds
provided directly to the Palestinian National Authority would be managed
with total transparency in a highly skilled and professional manner'.
Total international aid commitments to the Palestinians stand at about
Dollars 2.8bn over the next five years. This includes grants, concessionary
loans, loan guarantees and aid from the UN Relief and Works Agency.
About Dollars 2.1bn can be considered 'new' commitments made after the
interim self-rule agreement signed by Israel and the PLO in Washington on
September 13.
Some Dollars 800m has been pledged for the first year of interim Palestinian
self-rule but some donors, such as Saudi Arabia, have been reluctant to
commit themselves beyond that.
Officials in Riyadh, still angered by the PLO's support for Iraq during the
Gulf war, have said they wanted to be certain every dollar went to specific
infrastructure projects and nothing to Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman.
The World Bank is co-ordinating the international aid effort but has not
taken responsibility for liaising on specific projects or acting as a
channel for the flow of money to the Palestinian Economic Council for
Development and Reconstruction (Pecdar).
Fears had been raised among donors that the membership of Pecdar, headed by
Mr Arafat, was too heavily politicised and lacked technical expertise.
As a result it it likely that Pecdar's main board will only set the broad
policy outlines, leaving detailed work to Mr Ahmed Qurie, also known as Abu
Ala, director-general, and departments under him. Palestinians associated
with Pecdar insist they will soon have mechanisms for accounting and
maintaining control over the council's spending.
</TEXT>
